Protectionism is the practice of protecting domestic industry against foreign competition by means of tariffs, subsidies, import quotas, and other restrictions.

Protectionism is sometimes necessary in trade because it can help to protect domestic industries from unfair competition from foreign companies. For example, if a foreign company is dumping products in the domestic market at a price that is below the cost of production, this can put domestic companies at a disadvantage and lead to job losses. In such cases, protectionist measures can be used to level the playing field and prevent the domestic industry from being harmed.
